data.title: People with common Cork surnames could be heirs to huge UK fortunes
data.meta_description: Hundreds of Irish-born people have died in England or Wales with fortunes which are yet to be passed on - and anyone who can prove they are related could claim the inheritance

Estates from hundreds of Irish people who have died in England and Wales are yet to be claimed - with common Cork surnames like McCarthy, O'Leary and Murphy on the list.

When an individual dies without a will, the Government keeps tabs on whether a lawful heir has made a claim for their estate. If no claim is made within a set period, the money is instead put into the Government's pocket.

Prospective heirs have 12 years from the day of death to put in their claim on the estate in cases of unclaimed cash, or 30 years for other assets.

Anyone looking to put in a claim will be required to provide a family tree to prove their relation to the original owner of the estate.

READ MORE: Someone in Cork has won over €200k on the Lotto and is yet to come forward

READ MORE: Father of tragic Matthew Healy raising funds for charity to mark his son's 7th birthday

The website unclaimedestates.ie aims to help rightful heirs inherit estates.

As of today, it has 771 names of Irish-born people who have died in England or Wales and left fortunes which are yet to be passed on.

Below you will find their surname, first name, date of birth, place of birth, date of death and place of death - in that order.

Surnames are listed in alphabetical order so you can scroll through to see if you could be an heir to a fortune.
